   =20
 =20
Bill Hwang is a former hedge fund manager who most recently invested his ow=
n money through a family office that he called Archegos Capital Management.=
 Archegos  borrowed a lot of money from a bunch of banks to buy a whole ton=
 of about a dozen stocks. When Hwang bought these stocks, they went up a lo=
t. So he was able to borrow more money, which he did, and then he used that=
 money to buy more of the stocks, so they kept going up. Then one of them w=
ent down a bit, Hwang got a bunch of margin calls from the banks, he didn=
=E2=80=99t have any money left (it was all invested in the stocks), so the =
banks liquidated the stocks and they went all the way back down. Hwang=E2=
=80=99s money all disappeared, and some of the banks lost billions of dolla=
rs that they had loaned him.This was all just a very weird thing to do?[5]=
=C2=A0Hwang is a financially sophisticated guy, and it is hard to know how =
he thought this would go. But it went the obvious way and he lost all his m=
oney and caused a=C2=A0panic in the market for those dozen stocks, as well =
as big losses at a few of his banks.The panic and losses were high-profile =
enough that the US Justice Department and Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n looked into them, and in April they charged Hwang with some crimes. Speci=
fically:=09They argued that buying all those stocks was=C2=A0market manipul=
ation, because Hwang=E2=80=99s buying made them go up a ridiculous amount, =
and he should not have done that.=09They argued that Hwang borrowed all tha=
t money from his banks by lying to them about what he was doing, how concen=
trated his portfolio was, etc., which is bank fraud.When we  talked about t=
his=C2=A0in April, I was skeptical that this could be market manipulation. =
The problem is that the DOJ and SEC had no theory of=C2=A0what Hwang was tr=
ying to do. If you push up the price of some stocks because you have some g=
iant derivative trade on that makes money from the stocks going up, fine, m=
arket manipulation. But if you just generically push stocks up by buying th=
em, and then you sell them, they=E2=80=99ll go back down and you won=E2=80=
=99t make any money. Hwang doesn=E2=80=99t seem to have=C2=A0made money on =
this weird round-trip =E2=80=94=C2=A0he seems to have lost most of his mone=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0and nobody has any good ideas about=C2=A0how he=C2=A0could=
=C2=A0have. So what was the manipulative scheme?=C2=A0Yesterday Hwang=E2=80=
=99s lawyers filed a motion to dismiss the SEC case against him and honestl=
y it=E2=80=99s pretty compelling? Here is how it begins:The Complaint in th=
is matter is extraordinary: paragraph after paragraph alleges entirely lawf=
ul trading on the open market, but then concludes that the trades at issue=
=E2=80=94real trades subjecting defendant Bill Hwang to real economic risk,=
 and devoid of any deceptive actions=E2=80=94was somehow unlawful. In parti=
cular, the Complaint finds manipulation in defendant Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s c=
onduct in trading large volumes of securities, trading which the SEC second=
-guesses, in hindsight, was =E2=80=9Cnon-economic,=E2=80=9D i.e., lacked a =
legitimate economic basis. Along the way, the SEC declares to be unlawful a=
 number of practices that have long been accepted as entirely legitimate, i=
ncluding trading one=E2=80=99s own money through a family office that has l=
imited reporting requirements, trading on margin or through security-based =
swaps rather than in the securities themselves, or trading before or at the=
 end of the trading day. The result is a Complaint that is not only unprece=
dented in its expansion of the notion of =E2=80=9Copen-market manipulation,=
=E2=80=9D already a questionable theory, but one that would, if sustained, =
threaten the very existence of markets by allowing regulators to judge, in =
retrospect, the economic value of trading, and by equating manipulative int=
ent with mere knowledge of the truism that trading, and especially large tr=
ades, affects price. No trader could have known that these kinds of actions=
 would someday=E2=80=94because Mr. Hwang=E2=80=99s trading failed in the sh=
ort term, costing him, but no other investors, billions of dollar of losses=
=E2=80=94be deemed unlawful, rendering this Complaint not only wrong, but f=
undamentally unfair and an obvious attempt to rewrite the law and then appl=
y it retroactively.=C2=A0Look, if there=E2=80=99s a stock that trades at $5=
0, and you start buying a ton of it, and you keep buying it as it goes all =
the way up to $100, and then you sell it and it goes back down to $50, ther=
e was something=C2=A0weird=C2=A0about you buying at $100. Why did you buy i=
t at $100? It was not worth $100, apparently, as you can tell from the fact=
 that it traded at $50 before and after your buying spree. You were at leas=
t making a=C2=A0mistake=C2=A0buying it at $100, and because $100 is so much=
 more than $50 the mistake seems suspicious. It feels plausible to describe=
 your buying the stock at $100 as =E2=80=9Cnon-economic,=E2=80=9D like you =
were buying it for some reason other than that you thought it was worth $10=
0.=C2=A0But I don=E2=80=99t think that=E2=80=99s enough to count as market =
manipulation? Hwang=E2=80=99s motion discusses the law (citations omitted):=
The Supreme Court has characterized =E2=80=9Cmanipulation=E2=80=9D as a =E2=
=80=9Cterm of art=E2=80=9D in securities law. It therefore has held that a =
securities law violation for =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulation=E2=80=9D requires=
 a showing of =E2=80=9Cintentional or willful conduct designed to deceive o=
r defraud investors by controlling or artificially affecting the price of s=
ecurities.=E2=80=9D Similarly, the Court has held that to be actionable a m=
anipulation scheme must have a deceptive element.The deception requirement =
is met under Second Circuit law only by conduct that gives =E2=80=9Ca false=
 impression of how market participants value a security=E2=80=9D and disrup=
ts =E2=80=9Cthe natural interplay of supply and demand.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6W=
hile the SEC asserts that Archegos employed =E2=80=9Cmultiple deceptive tac=
tics=E2=80=9D and points to =E2=80=9Cseveral indicia of manipulation,=E2=80=
=9D it does not actually allege any purported deceptive acts that could hav=
e created =E2=80=9Ca false impression of how market participants value a se=
curity,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0but only alleges real trades that reflected how Mr. H=
wang valued securities and that exposed Archegos and Mr. Hwang to real econ=
omic risk. There are no allegations of the kinds of deceptive trading recog=
nized as creating an artificial market and price. Instead, the SEC=E2=80=99=
s truly radical theory is that Mr. Hwang engaged in a broad market manipula=
tion scheme over the entire six month =E2=80=9CRelevant Period=E2=80=9D bec=
ause his trading was so highly concentrated and so voluminous that it creat=
ed a market price that was somehow =E2=80=9Cartificial,=E2=80=9D which he a=
llegedly recognized and, on unspecified occasions, even intended. This theo=
ry of =E2=80=9Copen-market manipulation=E2=80=9D has been debated by legal =
scholars, but it has never been the basis for a cognizable cause of action =
in the Second Circuit or indeed in most other Circuits.=C2=A0The leading ca=
se on the subject in this Circuit is United States v. Mulheren. In Mulheren=
, the Court criticized the government=E2=80=99s open-market manipulation th=
eory and reversed a criminal conviction based upon it. Specifically, the go=
vernment alleged that the defendant bought stock with the sole intent of dr=
iving up its price as a favor to Ivan Boesky, who wanted to sell his shares=
 of the same stock back to the company when the stock hit a certain price. =
Allegations and proof that Boesky told Mulheren that =E2=80=9Cit would be g=
reat if it traded=E2=80=9D at the desired price, along with Mulheren=E2=80=
=99s use of a broker he did not regularly use (to allegedly conceal his tra=
ding activity), and that Mulheren=E2=80=99s purchases comprised 70% of the =
trading in that security between the opening of the market and 11:10 a.m. w=
ere, even taken together, insufficient to sustain a conviction for market m=
anipulation.=C2=A0The Court noted that all the evidence presented against M=
ulheren was at least as consistent with innocent behavior=E2=80=94buying st=
ock because he wanted to own it=E2=80=94as with manipulation.=C2=A0Similarl=
y, all the market-manipulation charges against Hwang are basically =E2=80=
=9Che bought stupid amounts of these stocks at stupid prices.=E2=80=9D In h=
indsight that is definitely true, and strange, but it is hard to see who he=
 deceived by doing that, or how it could be illegal. Maybe he just wanted t=
o own them.You could, I should say,=C2=A0try=C2=A0to make a manipulation ca=
se here. In the abstract, a=C2=A0compelling manipulation case would be some=
thing like:=09Hwang borrowed money to buy a bunch of stocks to make them go=
 up.=09When they went up, he borrowed more money to buy more and make them =
go up more.=09When they went up more, he borrowed more money and=C2=A0burie=
d it in his backyard.=09Then they went down, the money in his account went =
to zero, and his banks lost money.=09The money in his backyard was still th=
ere though.It is not exactly clear that this would count as market manipula=
tion under the relevant precedents, but it=C2=A0makes sense. It is a trade =
of the form =E2=80=9Cbuy stocks to make them go up so you can make money on=
 some other trade=E2=80=9D; here the other trade is borrowing a lot of mone=
y (secured by inflated stocks) to bury in your backyard. As far as I can te=
ll, though, there is absolutely no evidence of this; as far as I can tell H=
wang=C2=A0plowed most or all of his winnings back into this doomed trade. H=
e just wanted to own the stocks.The other charges against Hwang involve all=
eged lies to the banks to get them to lend Archegos more money. I am a litt=
le skeptical of those charges too: Credit Suisse Group AG, which lost a bun=
ch of money on Archegos,  released its own detailed report that made it pre=
tty clear that it was not really deceived about what Archegos was up to. St=
ill, if you lie to banks to get money, it is tough to argue =E2=80=9Cwell i=
t=E2=80=99s fine because they didn=E2=80=99t believe me.=E2=80=9D Hwang has=
 a better argument, though: He=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t do any of that lying; pe=
ople who worked for him at Archegos allegedly did:Mindful of its inability =
to allege any kind of deceit or fraudulent trading conduct, the SEC alleges=
 that swap counterparties were the victims of misstatements that caused the=
m to extend credit to Mr. Hwang=E2=80=99s fund, Archegos. But these misstat=
ements were not, even as alleged, those of Mr. Hwang but of others; the SEC=
 seeks to attribute them to Mr. Hwang only by arguing that he =E2=80=9Cset =
the tone=E2=80=9D for them.I don=E2=80=99t know. I get the point that if a =
bunch of stocks crash all at once, and banks lose billions of dollars, beca=
use of one guy=E2=80=99s weird trading, it is hard=C2=A0not=C2=A0to charge =
him with a crime. But it is a bit hard to know what the crime here was.
