ds even for a short while, according to market participants. The biggest gl=
obal banks -- including Citigroup Inc., Deutsche Bank AG, Goldman Sachs Gro=
up Inc. and JPMorgan Chase & Co. -- have been among those cutting back in p=
arts of the debt markets in Europe and the US, the people said.The pullback=
 means pockets of the market are grinding to a halt, posing a problem for a=
sset managers seeking to divest from securities at quick notice to meet red=
emption requests across credit funds. Earlier this month, investors pulled =
money out of European fixed income funds at the fastest pace since March 20=
20, according to a note published last week by BofA Global Research analyst=
s. US high-grade bond investors have now yanked cash for 13 consecutive wee=
ks, extending the longest losing streak on record.=E2=80=9CLiquidity has be=
en very poor, and when we need it the most,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0David Newman, chi=
ef investment officer for global high yield at Allianz Global Investors, sa=
id in an interview. =E2=80=9CIn some cases it=E2=80=99s taken us several we=
eks to exit what should be very liquid positions. Conversely, we=E2=80=99ve=
 been unable to buy positions that we think offer up opportunity.=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=A6The role of banks is crucial in bond markets because they=E2=80=99=
re typically traded in over-the-counter, or OTC, markets rather than on exc=
hanges like equities. Trades are also often much bigger, with bonds sold in=
