<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Celsius</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a financial literacy test for =
you:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: =
16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can borrow $18 billion=C2=
=A0at 8% interest.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can take th=
at money and invest it in loans=C2=A0that pay 20% interest.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t have to put up any of your own =
money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So you get $3.6 billion a y=
ear in interest (20% of $18 billion), and you pay out $1.4 billion in inter=
est (8% of $18 billion), so you keep about $2.2 billion for yourself.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Is this good?</li></ol><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">This is not a yes-or-no question, and the right answer is pro=
bably something like =E2=80=9Cwell, good for who?=E2=80=9D If you are a per=
son who invents a business like this, and you are able to do it for a year =
or two and squirrel away the $2.4 billion, it is very very good for you and=
 you can buy yachts and stuff. But in the long run, if you are borrowing at=
 8% and lending at 20%, you are taking some huge risk somewhere. Those 20% =
loans are risky and correlated and illiquid and possibly Ponzi schemes; tha=
t 8% money is flighty and unstable; you are lending out all the money you a=
re borrowing and there is no cushion anywhere. At some point the people len=
ding you the money at 8% are all going to ask for it back, and the people b=
orrowing the money at 20% aren=E2=80=99t going to give it back, and you=E2=
=80=99re not going to have the money to pay back the 8% people, and they=E2=
=80=99re going to be really mad, and that=E2=80=99s when it will be useful =
for you to have a yacht to sail away on.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An=
yway here=E2=80=99s a Wall Street Journal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/28218867.272582/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2x=
lcy9iZWhpbmQtdGhlLWNlbHNpdXMtc2FsZXMtcGl0Y2gtd2FzLWEtY3J5cHRvLWZpcm0tYnVpbH=
Qtb24tcmlzay0xMTY1NjQ5ODE0Mj9zdD04a2NqYTNmeThrZWRqcWE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBe002089d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">article about Celsius</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius Network LLC CEO Alex Mashinsky built his cryptocu=
rrency lender into a giant on a pitch that it was less risky than a bank wi=
th better returns for customers.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But =
investor documents show the lender carried far more risk than a traditional=
 bank.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lender issued numerous lar=
ge loans backed by little collateral, according to Celsius investor documen=
ts from 2021 reviewed by The Wall Street Journal. The documents show that C=
elsius had little cushion in the event of a downturn, and made investments =
that would be difficult to quickly unwind if customers raced to withdraw th=
eir money. Celsius didn=E2=80=99t respond to requests for comment from the =
Journal.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius had $19 billion of assets =
and roughly $1 billion of equity as of last summer, before it raised new fu=
nds, according to Celsius investor documents from 2021 reviewed by the Jour=
nal. The median assets-to-equity ratio for all the North American banks in =
the S&amp;P 1500 Composite index was about 9:1, or about half that of Celsi=
us, according to data from FactSet.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">We have talked a lot about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/28218867.272582/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMjgvZG9uLXQtY2hlYXQtb24tdGhlLWV0aGljcy1leGFtP=
2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1u=
ZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB44065788" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> crypto banks</a> recently, and Celsius=
=E2=80=99s roughly 5.3% capital ratio is, if anything,=C2=A0<em>high</em>. =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28218867.272582/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMTMvbWVyZ=
2VyLWJ1eWVyLXMtcmVtb3JzZS1zb21ldGltZXMtd29ya3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyOTIyX01PTkVZ=
U1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjI=
wNjI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf5171cd3" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> Tether=E2=80=99s</a> capital ratio is about 0.2% (!); <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28218867.272582/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMjMvcmV2bG9uLWlzLWdldHR=
pbmctbWVtZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG=
1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0d=
WZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb365b1a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Voyager Digital Ltd.=E2=80=
=99s</a> is about 4.3%. This banking business, this business of borrowing a=
t lower rates and lending at higher rates and having a thin sliver of equit=
y, this is a pretty well-known business, and in traditional banking there a=
re lots of safeguards around it. That sliver of equity can=E2=80=99t be too=
 slim, you need to keep some cash on hand to give back to your depositors, =
you need to make prudent loans that are not too risky or too concentrated o=
r too much to your own affiliates, etc. In traditional finance there are =
=E2=80=9Cshadow banks=E2=80=9D that try to do this sort of business with le=
ss regulation, but there are regulatory and market constraints on how much =
of that is allowed, particularly after shadow banking blew up in 2008. Mean=
while in crypto absolutely anything apparently goes.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28218=
867.272582/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjIt=
MDYtMTMvbWVyZ2VyLWJ1eWVyLXMtcmVtb3JzZS1zb21ldGltZXMtd29ya3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDY=
yOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Cf5171cd3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> talked about Celsius</a> a few weeks ago, and nothing h=
ere really comes as a surprise. =E2=80=9CSomebody is lying,=E2=80=9D Mashin=
sky <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28218867.27258=
2/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMjcvY2Vsc=
2l1cy1zLTE4LXlpZWxkcy1vbi1jcnlwdG8tYXJlLXRlbXB0aW5nLWFuZC1kcmF3aW5nLXNjcnV0=
aW55P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJ=
jZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZiN4aj=
R5N3Z6a2c_c3JlZj0xa0pWTnFuVQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9f2e48fe" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> on=
ce told Bloomberg Businessweek</a>: =E2=80=9CEither the bank is lying or Ce=
lsius is lying.=E2=80=9D That too was a kind of financial literacy test.=C2=
=A0Celsius has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/282=
18867.272582/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibG9nLmNlbHNpdXMubmV0d29yay9hLW1lbW8tdG8tdGhlLWNlbH=
NpdXMtY29tbXVuaXR5LTU5NTMyYTA2ZWNjNg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf1ef119c" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">frozen customer withdrawals</a> for weeks; regular banks, conspicuousl=
y, have not.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Journal article also=
 points to sort of a subtle fact about crypto banking and interconnection:<=
/p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Adding to Celsius=E2=80=99s lev=
erage was money borrowed from others including Tether International Ltd., w=
hich issues a cryptocurrency pegged to the U.S. dollar. As of last summer, =
Celsius had a credit facility for up to $1.1 billion from Tether, which its=
elf was an early investor in Celsius with a 7.8% stake in the lender as of =
last spring, Celsius told investors. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Li=
ke a bank, Celsius was able to pay yields to customers largely by making mo=
ney through lending at even higher yields to others.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">One of its biggest units was lending to other crypto financ=
ial businesses, including digital-asset manager Galaxy Digital and institut=
ional crypto-lending firm Genesis, Celsius told investors. Celsius projecte=
d in May 2021 that institutional lending would bring in about $290 million =
of revenue for the year, more than one-quarter of total revenue, the docume=
nts reviewed by the Journal show.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Whi=
le banks like loans to be overcollateralized=E2=80=94homeowners taking out =
a mortgage post their house as collateral, which is valued at more than the=
 loan=E2=80=94Celsius required its business borrowers to post only an avera=
ge of about 50% collateral on its $2.7 billion of loans as of last spring, =
the documents show. Undercollateralized lending is considered a risky pract=
ice, one that was more generous than that of many of Celsius=E2=80=99s comp=
etitors.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius used some of that co=
llateral to borrow more money itself, a process known as rehypothecation, a=
dding additional risk.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Think a=
bout how that business might work. At a high level of generality, you have =
two crypto financial businesses, perhaps they are Celsius and Genesis, or C=
elsius and Tether,=C2=A0or whatever, but let=E2=80=99s just call them Borro=
wer and Lender. Borrower has some Bitcoins (or Ether or whatever) and wants=
 dollars (or USDC stablecoins or Tether or whatever); Lender has plenty of =
dollars (USDC, Tether, etc.) that it is willing to lend. Borrower and Lende=
r get together and agree that Borrower=C2=A0will post its Bitcoins to Lende=
r as collateral, and Lender will hand over some dollars to Borrower collate=
ralized by those Bitcoins. Fine. A normal, collateralized margin loan.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How many Bitcoins should Borrower give Lender f=
or the dollars? Well, if you are Lender, you will want your loan to be well=
 secured. If Borrower=C2=A0gives you $200 worth of Bitcoin and you lend it=
=C2=A0$100 of cash, then you will be pretty well secured. If Borrower doesn=
=E2=80=99t pay you back the $100, you can seize its collateral and sell it =
for $200, giving you plenty of room to repay your loan. Even if the price o=
f Bitcoin falls by 10% or 20% or 40%, you can still sell the collateral for=
 enough to cover your loan. (If it falls by more than 50%, as it has this y=
ear, then you are in trouble, but you have margin calls to protect you alon=
g the way; you don=E2=80=99t have to wait for it to fall that far.) This is=
 the way that margin lending generally works in retail stock brokerage acco=
unts.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course everything is competitive a=
nd perhaps Lender will be willing to accept less than $200 worth of Bitcoin=
 for a $100 loan. Perhaps it will feel safe with $150 of collateral, or $12=
0. At some level of collateral, though, you stop feeling safe=C2=A0<em>abou=
t the collateral:=C2=A0</em>If you lend $100 of cash against $110 of Bitcoi=
n, Bitcoin is pretty volatile, and if it goes down by 10% your loan will be=
 undercollateralized. If you lend $100 against $110 of Bitcoin, you are mak=
ing a=C2=A0<em>credit=C2=A0</em>decision: You=E2=80=99re lending the $100 n=
ot only because you think Bitcoin is good collateral but also because you t=
hink Borrower is good for the money.=C2=A0<em>Certainly=C2=A0</em>if you le=
nd $100 of cash against $50 of Bitcoin, you are making=C2=A0<em>mostly=C2=
=A0</em>a credit decision; if Borrower vanishes then the best you=E2=80=99r=
e going to do is get $50 back.[1]=C2=A0You are counting on Borrower=C2=A0to=
 repay you, and you have done some underwriting to make you confident that =
Borrower is a good credit. Or you haven=E2=80=99t, I mean; Celsius has not =
exactly covered itself in glory in recent weeks. But let=E2=80=99s assume t=
hat you do, and you sensibly believe that you are making these (under-)coll=
ateralized loans to good strong businesses that should be able to pay you b=
ack even in a market downturn.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now let=
=E2=80=99s flip it around. Let=E2=80=99s say that you are Borrower, not Len=
der. You are handing over some Bitcoins and getting back dollars. You will =
have the use of Lender=E2=80=99s $100, and if you disappear Lender won=E2=
=80=99t get its money back and will have to seize your collateral. But noti=
ce that=C2=A0<em>Lender has the use of your Bitcoins, and if Lender disappe=
ars you won=E2=80=99t get your Bitcoins back</em>. Of course if that happen=
s you can keep the $100.[2]=C2=A0But if Lender disappears with $200 of your=
 Bitcoins then that=E2=80=99s not too much consolation.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">In other words, these transactions are completely symmetrical,=
 and if you are posting crypto collateral with a crypto lender then=C2=A0<e=
m>you=C2=A0</em>are taking=C2=A0<em>their=C2=A0</em>credit risk. (Notice, h=
ere, that Celsius was not in the business of keeping collateral in separate=
 vaults with the borrowers=E2=80=99 names taped on them, or of taking conti=
ngent claims on assets that sat in the borrowers=E2=80=99 wallets: It was r=
ehypothecating the collateral for its own use.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">And so if you are a big reputable well-managed crypto firm, and you wa=
nt to borrow $100 from Celsius, you might want to only post $50 of Bitcoin =
as collateral, not only because that is more efficient for you (you get mor=
e money for less collateral) but also because it is=C2=A0<em>safer=C2=A0</e=
m>for you. If Celsius goes bust or pauses withdrawals and hangs on to your =
$50 of Bitcoin, well, you still have their $100, it=E2=80=99s fine.[3]=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I should say that in traditional financ=
e there is a lot of this symmetrical risk: If I post Treasury bonds to borr=
ow cash from you, then I have your cash and you have my Treasuries and we b=
oth want to get our stuff back and worry that we won=E2=80=99t. Traditional=
 finance deals with this in various ways:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: =
decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Legal regimes that give us some sort of priority claim=C2=A0to gett=
ing our stuff back if the other one goes bust.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Third-party custody, where some super-safe entity holds the Tr=
easuries so you can=E2=80=99t run off with them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">The lenders (who tend to be overcollateralized =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0that is, I tend to post Treasuries worth more than the cash you give me =
back) are often big regulated banks or money-market funds, so I am relying =
on the regulatory system to make sure that you don=E2=80=99t actually go bu=
st or run off with my Treasuries.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
Long-standing cultures and best practices of credit risk management where, =
for instance, you will do some due diligence on my credit, and I will send =
you my audited financial statements, and you will have concentration limits=
 where you can=E2=80=99t invest all your money with me, etc.=C2=A0</li></ol=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I guess you could im=
agine ways to deal with this in crypto? I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/28218867.272582/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMTEtMTkvdXAtbmV4dC1jcnlwdG9jdXJyZW5jeS1nb2VzLX=
RvLXRoZS1tb29uP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmd=
XRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlz=
dHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB04411648" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">used to joke</a>, about =
everything, that =E2=80=9Csmart contracts via crypto make this super doable=
.=E2=80=9D You could imagine a smart contract where I put up Bitcoins and y=
ou put up USDC and if either of us runs into some sort of problem trigger t=
hen the thing automatically unwinds. And there are things like this in the =
world of decentralized finance. But actual big-dollar crypto leverage seems=
 to be built mainly on bilateral over-the-counter arrangements rather than =
smart contracts.[4]=C2=A0And some crypto lenders probably import credit-ris=
k-management best practices from traditional finance and adapt them in smar=
t ways to the realities of crypto! And some of them absolutely don=E2=80=99=
t.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have been writing a lot around here ab=
out how crypto is having its version of the 2008 financial crisis. One sche=
matic way to tell the story of 2008 would be to focus on =E2=80=9Cshadow ba=
nking.=E2=80=9D The basic business of banking is borrowing short-term from =
people who think their money is very safe, and invest it in longer-term loa=
ns that have some risk. That is a dangerous business, and so it is heavily =
regulated. And in the lead-up to 2008, people in the financial industry fou=
nd ways to re-create that dangerous=C2=A0sort of business in ways that were=
 less heavily regulated, so they could be more aggressive about leverage an=
d liquidity and concentration and credit risk. And nobody realized how much=
 of this there was, and how dangerous it was, and how interconnected it was=
 with the rest of the financial system, until it popped.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">And then they did realize, and there was a broad after-the-fa=
ct crackdown on shadow banking, and now through some combination of regulat=
ion and temperament and bad memories there is just less of this sort of thi=
ng in traditional finance. Still lots! But=C2=A0less of it,=C2=A0more const=
rained, less leveraged. Everyone in traditional finance has seen this movie=
 before and knows how it ends.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And ye=
t there is some =E2=80=A6=C2=A0natural =E2=80=A6=C2=A0human =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=
longing =E2=80=A6 to borrow short and lend long with no equity? I dunno. Si=
nce 2008, the traditional financial industry has tried to suppress that des=
ire. But it found a home in crypto.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored=
