prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;"> borrowed a lot of money</a> from a bunch of banks to buy a whole ton o=
f about a dozen stocks. When Hwang bought these stocks, they went up a lot.=
 So he was able to borrow more money, which he did, and then he used that m=
oney to buy more of the stocks, so they kept going up. Then one of them wen=
t down a bit, Hwang got a bunch of margin calls from the banks, he didn=E2=
=80=99t have any money left (it was all invested in the stocks), so the ban=
ks liquidated the stocks and they went all the way back down. Hwang=E2=80=
=99s money all disappeared, and some of the banks lost billions of dollars =
that they had loaned him.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was all just=
 a very weird thing to do?[5]=C2=A0Hwang is a financially sophisticated guy=
, and it is hard to know how he thought this would go. But it went the obvi=
ous way and he lost all his money and caused a=C2=A0panic in the market for=
 those dozen stocks, as well as big losses at a few of his banks.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The panic and losses were high-profile enough that t=
he US Justice Department and Securities and Exchange Commission looked into=
 them, and in April they charged Hwang with some crimes. Specifically:</p><=
ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They argued that buying all those stoc=
ks was=C2=A0<em>market manipulation</em>, because Hwang=E2=80=99s buying ma=
de them go up a ridiculous amount, and he should not have done that.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They argued that Hwang borrowed all th=
at money from his banks by lying to them about what he was doing, how conce=
ntrated his portfolio was, etc., which is <em>bank fraud</em>.</li></ol><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/28218867.272582/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjcvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1hcnJlc3QtaW5zaWRlLXRoZS12aWNpb3=
VzLWN5Y2xlLW9mLWFyY2hlZ29zLWNvbGxhcHNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJ=
nV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyOSZ1=
dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb002b829" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 talked about this=C2=A0in April</a>, I was skeptical that this could be ma=
rket manipulation. The problem is that the DOJ and SEC had no theory of=C2=
=A0<em>what Hwang was trying to do</em>. If you push up the price of some s=
tocks because you have some giant derivative trade on that makes money from=
 the stocks going up, fine, market manipulation. But if you just genericall=
y push stocks up by buying them, and then you sell them, they=E2=80=99ll go=
 back down and you won=E2=80=99t make any money. Hwang doesn=E2=80=99t seem=
 to have=C2=A0made money on this weird round-trip =E2=80=94=C2=A0he seems t=
o have lost most of his money =E2=80=94=C2=A0and nobody has any good ideas =
about=C2=A0how he=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>have. So what was the manipulati=
ve scheme?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday Hwang=E2=80=99s =
lawyers filed <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2821=
8867.272582/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmR=
meElVL3JjVTFhTkd0MjIzZy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB00987a77" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a mo=
tion to dismiss the SEC case</a> against him and honestly it=E2=80=99s pret=
ty compelling? Here is how it begins:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The Complaint in this matter is extraordinary: paragraph after parag=
raph alleges entirely lawful trading on the open market, but then concludes=
 that the trades at issue=E2=80=94real trades subjecting defendant Bill Hwa=
ng to real economic risk, and devoid of any deceptive actions=E2=80=94was s=
omehow unlawful. In particular, the Complaint finds manipulation in defenda=
nt Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s conduct in trading large volumes of securities, tra=
ding which the SEC second-guesses, in hindsight, was =E2=80=9Cnon-economic,=
=E2=80=9D i.e., lacked a legitimate economic basis. Along the way, the SEC =
declares to be unlawful a number of practices that have long been accepted =
as entirely legitimate, including trading one=E2=80=99s own money through a=
 family office that has limited reporting requirements, trading on margin o=
r through security-based swaps rather than in the securities themselves, or=
 trading before or at the end of the trading day. The result is a Complaint=
 that is not only unprecedented in its expansion of the notion of =E2=80=9C=
open-market manipulation,=E2=80=9D already a questionable theory, but one t=
hat would, if sustained, threaten the very existence of markets by allowing=
 regulators to judge, in retrospect, the economic value of trading, and by =
equating manipulative intent with mere knowledge of the truism that trading=
, and especially large trades, affects price. No trader could have known th=
at these kinds of actions would someday=E2=80=94because Mr. Hwang=E2=80=99s=
 trading failed in the short term, costing him, but no other investors, bil=
lions of dollar of losses=E2=80=94be deemed unlawful, rendering this Compla=
int not only wrong, but fundamentally unfair and an obvious attempt to rewr=
ite the law and then apply it retroactively.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look, if there=E2=80=99s a stock that trades at $50, a=
nd you start buying a ton of it, and you keep buying it as it goes all the =
way up to $100, and then you sell it and it goes back down to $50, there wa=
s something=C2=A0<em>weird=C2=A0</em>about you buying at $100. Why did you =
buy it at $100? It was not worth $100, apparently, as you can tell from the=
 fact that it traded at $50 before and after your buying spree. You were at=
 least making a=C2=A0<em>mistake=C2=A0</em>buying it at $100, and because $=
100 is so much more than $50 the mistake seems suspicious. It feels plausib=
le to describe your buying the stock at $100 as =E2=80=9Cnon-economic,=E2=
=80=9D like you were buying it for some reason other than that you thought =
it was worth $100.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I don=E2=80=99=
t think that=E2=80=99s enough to count as market manipulation? Hwang=E2=80=
=99s motion discusses the law (citations omitted):</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Supreme Court has characterized =E2=80=9Cmanipulat=
ion=E2=80=9D as a =E2=80=9Cterm of art=E2=80=9D in securities law. It there=
fore has held that a securities law violation for =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulat=
ion=E2=80=9D requires a showing of =E2=80=9Cintentional or willful conduct =
designed to deceive or defraud investors by controlling or artificially aff=
ecting the price of securities.=E2=80=9D Similarly, the Court has held that=
 to be actionable a manipulation scheme must have a deceptive element.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deception requirement is met under Second C=
ircuit law only by conduct that gives =E2=80=9Ca false impression of how ma=
rket participants value a security=E2=80=9D and disrupts =E2=80=9Cthe natur=
al interplay of supply and demand.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">While the SEC asserts that Archegos employed =E2=80=9Cmultiple d=
eceptive tactics=E2=80=9D and points to =E2=80=9Cseveral indicia of manipul=
ation,=E2=80=9D it does not actually allege any purported deceptive acts th=
at could have created =E2=80=9Ca false impression of how market participant=
s value a security,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0but only alleges real trades that reflect=
ed how Mr. Hwang valued securities and that exposed Archegos and Mr. Hwang =
to real economic risk. There are no allegations of the kinds of deceptive t=
rading recognized as creating an artificial market and price. Instead, the =
SEC=E2=80=99s truly radical theory is that Mr. Hwang engaged in a broad mar=
ket manipulation scheme over the entire six month =E2=80=9CRelevant Period=
=E2=80=9D because his trading was so highly concentrated and so voluminous =
that it created a market price that was somehow =E2=80=9Cartificial,=E2=80=
=9D which he allegedly recognized and, on unspecified occasions, even inten=
ded. This theory of =E2=80=9Copen-market manipulation=E2=80=9D has been deb=
ated by legal scholars, but it has never been the basis for a cognizable ca=
use of action in the Second Circuit or indeed in most other Circuits.=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The leading case on the subject in this Ci=
rcuit is United States v. Mulheren. In Mulheren, the Court criticized the g=
overnment=E2=80=99s open-market manipulation theory and reversed a criminal=
 conviction based upon it. Specifically, the government alleged that the de=
fendant bought stock with the sole intent of driving up its price as a favo=
r to Ivan Boesky, who wanted to sell his shares of the same stock back to t=
he company when the stock hit a certain price. Allegations and proof that B=
oesky told Mulheren that =E2=80=9Cit would be great if it traded=E2=80=9D a=
t the desired price, along with Mulheren=E2=80=99s use of a broker he did n=
ot regularly use (to allegedly conceal his trading activity), and that Mulh=
eren=E2=80=99s purchases comprised 70% of the trading in that security betw=
een the opening of the market and 11:10 a.m. were, even taken together, ins=
ufficient to sustain a conviction for market manipulation.=C2=A0The Court n=
oted that all the evidence presented against Mulheren was at least as consi=
stent with innocent behavior=E2=80=94buying stock because he wanted to own =
it=E2=80=94as with manipulation.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Similarly, all the market-manipulation charges against Hwang are b=
asically =E2=80=9Che bought stupid amounts of these stocks at stupid prices=
.=E2=80=9D In hindsight that is definitely true, and strange, but it is har=
d to see who he deceived by doing that, or how it could be illegal. Maybe h=
e just wanted to own them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could, I sho=
uld say,=C2=A0<em>try=C2=A0</em>to make a manipulation case here. In the ab=
stract, a=C2=A0compelling manipulation case would be something like:</p><ol=
 style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Hwang borrowed money to buy a bunch of=
 stocks to make them go up.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When t=
hey went up, he borrowed more money to buy more and make them go up more.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When they went up more, he borrowed=
 more money and=C2=A0<em>buried it in his backyard</em>.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then they went down, the money in his account went=
 to zero, and his banks lost money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">The money in his backyard was still there though.</li></ol><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">It is not exactly clear that this would count as market mani=
pulation under the relevant precedents, but it=C2=A0<em>makes sense</em>. I=
t is a trade of the form =E2=80=9Cbuy stocks to make them go up so you can =
make money on some other trade=E2=80=9D; here the other trade is borrowing =
a lot of money (secured by inflated stocks) to bury in your backyard. As fa=
r as I can tell, though, there is absolutely no evidence of this; as far as=
 I can tell Hwang=C2=A0plowed most or all of his winnings back into this do=
omed trade. He just wanted to own the stocks.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The other charges against Hwang involve alleged lies to the banks to get=
 them to lend Archegos more money. I am a little skeptical of those charges=
